Explanation:

I inspected the ConsumerController.getConsumerInfo method. It is secured with @Secured("ROLE_USER") and mapped to GET /consumer/info. The method builds a JsonObject response using Gson and returns a JSON string. When the authenticated principal exists and a matching Consumer is found, the response contains:

- "consumer": a serialized Consumer object (Gson is configured with an AnnotationExclusionStrategy that excludes fields annotated with @Exclude; Consumer.printrequests and Consumer.notifications are annotated @Exclude and will be omitted).
- "success": true

If the principal is missing or no Consumer is found, the response contains only "success": false. The controller method itself always returns an HTTP 200 response body (String) when invoked, but authentication may prevent reaching the method (leading to 401/403 responses from Spring Security). For completeness I include 401 in the responses list.

I examined the Consumer class and its supertype User, and the dependent types to build the inline schema (no $ref). Relevant serialized Consumer fields (per Gson configuration) are:

- From User: id (long), username (string), password (string), roles (array of strings)
- From Consumer: name (string), email (string), latitude (string), longitude (string), printingSchemas (array of PrintingSchema)
- printingSchemas elements: id (long), name (string), paperSpecs (string), bindingSpecs (string), coverSpecs (string), deleted (boolean)
- balance: Money object with currency (string), integerPart (integer), fractionalPart (integer)

The response object for 200 therefore is an object with "success" (boolean) and optionally "consumer" (object) matching the structure above. 401 is provided with a simple description and no schema.

